DDS to FFT Integration & Fixed-Point Verification
Project Overview
This repository contains the hardware integration and verification flow for a Digital Signal Processing (DSP) datapath, specifically connecting a Direct Digital Synthesizer (DDS) to a Fast Fourier Transform (FFT) module.

The primary goal of this stage is to verify the mathematical integrity of the physical hardware (Verilog RTL) against a custom bit-accurate fixed-point MATLAB model.

Architecture & Data Flow
The datapath simulates the sensing/radar portion of an Integrated Sensing and Communication (ISAC) system. The flow operates as follows:

Signal Generation (DDS): A hardware DDS generates a digital sine wave (raw integers).

Data Handoff: The RTL output of the DDS is captured in text files to act as the test vector.

FFT Processing (Hardware): The captured DDS data is fed into the Verilog FFT module (Radix-2² DIF architecture).

FFT Processing (Software Model): The exact same DDS data is scaled and fed into a custom, fixed-point MATLAB FFT model (radix22_dif_fft_fixed.m) parameterized to match the hardware's exact word length (WL) and fractional length (FL).

Comparison: The outputs from both the RTL and the MATLAB model are compared to calculate signal degradation and noise introduction.

Verification Methodology
To ensure the hardware is performing optimally without catastrophic overflow or unacceptable quantization noise, we utilize a Bit-Accurate Verification Flow.

Instead of comparing the hardware output to an ideal floating-point fft() (which naturally results in mismatch due to fixed-point truncation), we compare the RTL against a constrained MATLAB model.

Model Parameters
Datapath Width (WL): 16-bit

Fractional Precision (FL): 14-bit (Q2.14 format)

Rounding Scheme: Convergent

Overflow Handling: 16-bit signed integer wrap-around simulation

Verification Steps
Run the DDS RTL simulation and export the output to rtl_output.txt.

Run the MATLAB preparation script to format the integers for the FFT testbench.

Run the FFT RTL simulation using the generated input files.

Execute output_verification.m to compute the MATLAB fixed-point reference and compare it against the RTL output.

Performance Results
The fixed-point hardware implementation successfully matches the theoretical fixed-point model with exceptional accuracy.

FFT Size: 4096-point

Signal-to-Quantization-Noise Ratio (SQNR): ~50 dB

Error Vector Magnitude (EVM RMS): 0.331%

An EVM of 0.331% indicates highly pristine signal quality, providing massive safety margins well below the typical 1.5% threshold required for high-order modulation schemes like 256-QAM in the downstream communication path. The ~50 dB SQNR confirms that the intermediate bit-growth and truncation strategies inside the butterfly stages are functioning correctly without destroying fractional precision.